The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Sunday, May 23, 2004 				 Ministry boost to minorities
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, May 22: Minorities and Dalits never had it so good. Against a lone Muslim member in the outgoing Vajpayee government, Manmohan Singhs council of ministers has as many as seven Muslims and two Christians and eight members belonging to scheduled castes and tribes.																								Among the Muslim cabinet ministers are Ghulam Nabi Azad and P.M. Sayeed, who lost the Lakshadweep Lok Sabha election for the first time since 1957  by a mere 71 votes.																								The ministers of state are M. Shakeel Ahmed, Rehman Khan (both Congress), Mohammed Taslimuddin and M.A.A. Fatmi (RJD), all from Bihar and E. Ahmed of the Indian Union of Muslim League from Kerala.																								The Christians are Oscar Fernandes from Karnataka and Jagdish Tytler from Delhi  both from the Congress.																								Scheduled caste members Ram Vilas Paswan (Lok Jan Shakti Party) and Meira Kumar (Congress) and scheduled tribe member P.R. Kyndiah of the Congress have been given cabinet berths.																								SC/ST members given minister of state posts are Kumari Selja, Narayan Bhai Ratwa, K.H. Muniappa, Kantilal Bhuria, Manikrao Gavit and Namonarayan Meena  all from the Congress.
